node.text: This is the joint I use to make decorative frames for kumiko panels. It’s a half lap joint with offset shoulders to fill the rabbet. The rabbet is exactly half the parts’ thickness and I leave the dado set at that height when I cut the cheeks. It’s super efficient and strong joint. I also like that the joiner lines, which are square, mirror the joinery lines in the kumiko panel’s frame.

node.text: I first experimented with kumiko in 2015. It was a small decision to do so, really, but that decision pushed a small pebble down a snowy slope, and over the last six years it’s picked up speed and mass, and now it’s an avalanche. I would not have financially survived COVID were it not for kumiko, and I wouldn’t have a book that’s been translated into three languages, either. Now there’s an online course with @domestika that has subtitles in seven or eight languages. (Link in profile for details.) It’s amazing how small decisions grow on their own, weaving together with other small decisions until one day you’ve made a wonderful life and career from them, and you end up somewhere you never even thought to imagine.

node.text: I’d be surprised if you’d missed it (because I’ve been tooted my own horn about it so much!), but in case you did: My @domestika kumiko course is now open for registration. In the course, I walk you through how to make the frame and patterns for a kumiko panel that I designed. The folks at @domestika do an awesome job creating their courses and telling a story while also providing excellent instruction. Check out the link in my profile for details. If you sign up for the class using that link, I see far more financial benefit than if you do it not using the link. A huge thanks to everyone that has signed up so far!

node.text: The kumiko panel that I show how to make in my course on @domestika uses my two favorite patterns: a “hashtag” spun 45º and the ads-no-ha. The hashtag one is so simply but creates a beautiful, complex pattern when rotated 45º. Check out the link in my profile for details about the course. So far, the response has been great! Thanks to everyone that has signed up so far!

node.text: I’m super excited today, because my kumiko with @domestika is now available for registration, with the actual course going live next Friday. This is a great opportunity to learn kumiko by making a beautiful panel that has two different patterns in it. The folks at @domestika produce amazing online classes. The link in my profile takes you to details.

My next book is just about ready to go the printer! Proofing it now. And I have a few photos to send in.

node.text: Today is day 1 of 6 for my class at Maine Coast Workshop in Camden, Maine. We are making this tea cabinet. The pull broke off the original when I was transporting it in my truck. I have them just need glue them back on. It’s also my 49th birthday, and like the cabinet I’m a little worse for the wear but still reasonable appealing. Hahah.

node.text:
My next book is called “Build Better Boxes” and it comes out this Fall. I’ve always felt a bit weird about the title, because it sound a little arrogant, but here’s what I was thinking when I came up with it.
-
But there is something beyond the function that matters, something bigger than utility that you should be aiming for when you make boxes and furniture: beauty, purpose, and meaning. When I design and make a box, I think about what happens to it after it leaves my shop, how it will fit into the home and the daily life of the person that owns it. As I see it, the box’s purpose is to become woven into the fabric of the owner’s life, to become something valued, cherished, and loved. My goal for the box is that it become a meaningful part of their life, that it have sentimental value. Certainly, the box must perform its function well to achieve this goal, but more importantly it must be beautiful. It must feel good in the hand, and beckon the owner to use it. A better box is a beautiful box, an inviting box, a meaningful box. 
-
The techniques I demonstrate in this box are less important than what you make with them. Be thoughtful about design, pay attention to beauty, and think of the person for whom you are making the box. Embody your attention, your love, and your desire to do good in the box. Make your box better by making it an expression of your creativity, your humanity. I’ve tried to do that with the boxes, and I hope that inspire you to get out into the shop and create work that embodies who you are and that will be cherished for generations to come.
